			<title>Conformity in China</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=62865&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 07 Mar 2009 04:43:29 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Main point of this postessay: to share some reflections on American and Asian culture gained through a mundane experience. 
 
I had an interesting cross-cultural experience recently. I needed to explain a behavioral issue involving invoking the term "conformity" (super-idiotic things Chinese...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><i>Main point of this postessay: to share some reflections on American and Asian culture gained through a mundane experience.</i><br />
<br />
I had an interesting cross-cultural experience recently. I needed to explain a behavioral issue involving invoking the term &quot;conformity&quot; (super-idiotic things Chinese companies do, IS THIS CONTINENT A KINDERGARTEN??), when I realized I wasn't sure I knew the proper word. I decided to ask around among some really smart guys - 3 different Chinese grads of Princeton, Cornell, and Columbia, which word is proper in English. None of them knew. I could get them on board with the English, but nobody had a clue about the Chinese. I revoked their Ivy League diplomas on the spot. <br />
<br />
<i>Strange</i>. Asian culture is ruled by conformity. <br />
<br />
I took to the internet. After fishing around internet encyclopedias and academic journal database subscriptions, I found a few possibilities (&#36981;&#20174;&#65292;&#39034;&#20174;&#65292;&#22857;&#20174;&#65289; The Wikipedia/Baidu article on &quot;Authoritarianism&quot; cites conformism as an important element of dictatorships, apparently translated from English. Baidu has an article on &quot;The Theory of Social Confirmism&quot; - a communist primer on the free media's ability to inculcate people with the values of the bourgeoisie, partially mis-attributed to Paul Lazarsfeld.<br />
<br />
It struck me. Here I am in the society where conformity is not just something people do, it's the Second Commandment of China, just after &quot;Thou shalt honor thy mother and father.&quot;  It's like someone clipping a rosebush every day but never saying anything about &quot;rosebush&quot;, to the point of forgetting what the thing's called.<br />
<br />
That, I think, is one of the great things about America compared to Asia. Even as the corpses were piling up, nobody in China ever thought of questioning the idiotic shit they were conforming to. Peculiarly, histories of 19th-20th century China repeatedly use a contraction for &quot;conformist citizens&quot;  (&#39034;&#27665;) - conforming to the values of whoever has power; Confucians, Nationalists, Communists, and now Westernism. &quot;Conformist citizen&quot; is the usual explanation for massacre and mass starvation. All it takes is for one moron (Mao Zedong) to force his opinions on a nation of conformist sheep to have people burying all their rice in 20-foot deep &quot;growth wells&quot; and go on the wild, random rampages of the cultural revolution.<br />
<br />
That's where America and Europe(to a lesser extent) differ. It's individualistic. If the many are stupid bleating sheep, we voice an opinion. We disagree. We find a better way. America is the most individualistic and anti-conformist country in the world. Certainly, some people will try to gain authority or power over others by invoking social conformity. In China, this would work; it's good as mind control. In America, not so much. We understand &quot;conformism&quot; and can resist inappropriate forms of social control. While anyone with an objective willingly conforms to certain norms, we are also free do the right thing when necessary; we never became a fascist country, and good men opposed slavery and jim crow from the outset.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
